![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/anishathalye/neural-style/9b107ee074490183b3c29062cda8ce6838f37bbd/examples/1-output.jpg)

Nice!

If you have a good example, wanna add it to the readme?

OK I tried on Linux Ubuntu and same problem.  'data' is valid - I added a print statement in vgg.py.  If I print the keys, there is no 'normalization' key:

['layers', '**version**', 'meta', '**header**', '**globals**']

Hello,
I am running into the same issue.
I am on Ubuntu 14.04, 64 bits, using scipy 0.13.3.
Oh wow, weird. Maybe it's an issue with older versions of SciPy?

With some difficulty, I upgrade to scipy to 0.16 and it still doesn't work
for me (ubuntu 14.04).

I'm now installing MATLAB and saving the mat file in a different way...wish
me luck...

Huh, that's really weird. I haven't had problems with it on Ubuntu 14.04 or Mac OS X. I've also had a couple friends try this, and they haven't had issues.

If I print the keys, I get: `['layers', '__header__', '__globals__', 'classes', '__version__', 'normalization']`

I don't know how to print the keys with python so I looked at the mat file on matlab.
The 'normalization' structure is under a key called 'meta'.
By changing the code to include this change, I get rid of the previous error, but get a new one.

Line of code changed:
from:     mean = data['normalization'][0][0][0]
to:    mean = data['meta']['normalization'][0][0][0]

Error received after the change:
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "neural_style.py", line 122, in <module>
    main()
  File "neural_style.py", line 108, in main
    checkpoint_iterations=options.checkpoint_iterations)
  File "/home/smart/Documents/ConvNet/neural-style/stylize.py", line 24, in stylize
    net, mean_pixel = vgg.net(network, image)
  File "/home/smart/Documents/ConvNet/neural-style/vgg.py", line 24, in net
    mean_pixel = np.mean(mean, axis=(0, 1))
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/numpy/core/fromnumeric.py", line 2874, in mean
    out=out, keepdims=keepdims)
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/numpy/core/_methods.py", line 56, in _mean
    rcount = _count_reduce_items(arr, axis)
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/numpy/core/_methods.py", line 50, in _count_reduce_items
    items *= arr.shape[ax]
IndexError: tuple index out of range

It seams that it relates to the way the mean_pixel variable is calculated, at the following line.
I tried to change the 'axis' option to 'axis=(1, 2)' instead of 'axis=(0, 1)', but the error remained.

Oh wow, apparently the issue is that the MatConvNet people changed their data format...

See http://www.vlfeat.org/matconvnet/pretrained/#older-file-versions

The file that I was linking to has moved here: http://www.vlfeat.org/matconvnet/models/beta16/imagenet-vgg-verydeep-19.mat

I'll update the README for now, but at some point, the code should probably be updated for the new version.

My version: `MD5 (imagenet-vgg-verydeep-19.mat) = 8ee3263992981a1d26e73b3ca028a123`

The current version: `MD5 (imagenet-vgg-verydeep-19.mat) = b9b4a9eb1c2fb3b50e1ec1aca6f22342`
Oh wait. The link to the "old version" is broken - they're still serving the new version... :/

The link you provided two messages ago seems to work for me.

Confirmed.  That also worked for me.  Thanks for being so quick about this.

FYI...I'm getting over 10X speedup on my Tesla GPU as well.

( Note:  I also had to downgrade to numpy 1.1 because recent versions don't
have numpy.matmul defined, which is used in vgg.py )

I may try porting this to Torch7 to see if I can get any more speedup....
